                <fr:title text="FM Gradient Equivalence"><fr:link href="/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" title="Flow Matching for Generative Modeling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023/" display-uri="lipmanFlowMatchingGenerative2023" type="local">FM</fr:link> Gradient Equivalence</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);">Proof.</html:span> 

</html:div>
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>which is supposedly a "good" approximation of the data distribution <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>. We can then show that a <html:em>conditional flow matching loss</html:em> has the same gradient as the full <html:em>flow matching loss</html:em> i.e. our vector field should converge to the <html:em>marginal vector field</html:em>, which is a good approximation for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>.
 </html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
